 each of the road projects, even getting deeply involved in questions of exact routing as worries arose that the road would benefit some more than others. Connectivity was a key recurring theme as people imagined the prosperity that will come by being connected to other parts of the country and with other parts of the world. Sweeping in scope and conceptually ambitious, Roads tells a story of global flows of money, goods, and people—and of attempts to stabilize inherently unstable physical and social environments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnologyzPeru. 0aInfrastructurexPolitical aspectszPeru. 0aInfrastructurexSocial aspectszPeru. 0aRoadsxPolitical aspectszPeru. 0aRoadsxSocial aspectszPeru. 4aAnthropology. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies.  asocial anthropology, international highway construction, public and private collaboration on social projects, global flows of culture.1 aKnox, Hannah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145646640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801456466/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles